ism should be defined and what it means in countries with an established parliamentary system, particularly in the new democracies of Central and Eastern Europe. The key question this book addresses is: will the specific experience of communism and its aftermath give birth to a new distinct current of liberal thought, or will it simply enlarge the scope of the Western liberal debate? The authors argue that liberalism cannot be reduced merely to private property and market prices, but needs a very complex set of institutions and corresponding law. Contributors come from both sides of the former Iron Curtain and they highlight the richness and diversity of liberalism and discuss different perceptions of liberal thinking in the East and West in the post-modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aTransition, regime change.  aethics.  apostcommunism.1 aAcham, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAudard, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrowley, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirard, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGräfin Dönhoff, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLöwenstein, Bedrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMusil, Jirí, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMusil, Jiří, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPejovich, Svetozar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPra